args:
The tears in space turn out to be a side effect of
the Askran Kingdom's gateway-opening powers.
Sharena explains that Alfonse was captured by
Thórr—who calls herself the god of war—and
sent to this world. Hoping to save Alfonse,
the party decides to gather more information.
I know, right? Welcome to the Halidom!\nEr, I mean...welcome to our entire world?
Thanks! I appreciate all the hospitality,\nespecially after popping out of a gate\nuninvited the way I did.

You're always welcome here, Sharena.
And I apologize for dragging you into
a battle instead of giving you the proper
reception you deserve.
You didn't drag me into anything.\nIn fact, I am likely the one who\nshould be offering up apologies.
Are you referring to when you said the\nsource of the rifts was related to the\npower of your family?
If so, could you tell us more?
Certainly. So as I am sure my brother\ntold you, the royal family of Askr has\nthe ability to open gates.
Now, we are very good at opening gates\nto worlds that have stable ＂doors.＂\nBut in a world like this...
Right, I remember. This world is unstable\ncompared to yours, and highly sensitive\nto your powers.
Which causes new passages to open up all\nover the place.
So that means that Alfonse has come to\nthis world, yeah?
Actually, my brother was\ncaptured during a battle.
That guy's tougher than a box of old nails.\nHard to imagine anybody gettin' the\nbetter of him in a fight.
Good point, Ranzal. His foe must have\nbeen very powerful indeed.
Yes. She is Thórr—or ＂the god of war,＂\nas she insists on calling herself.
And she is a powerful enemy indeed.
We fought her with everything we had,\nbut she still ended up taking my brother.
I'm so sorry to hear that, Sharena.\nEr, but why did Thórr bring him here?
Because she has business in this place.\nMy brother is just a means to that end.
What could she want from us?\nWe don't even KNOW this woman!
I don't know. Not exactly, anyway.
But she said something about ＂judging the\nworthiness of certain otherworldly heroes\nas warriors for the heavens.＂
She also said she would use my brother's\npower to reach the ＂dragonblood realm.＂\nI figured she must have meant this world.
＂The dragonblood realm,＂ is it? Well,\nthat does seem an apt description.
But what's the part about judging\nthe worth of heroes?
Sounds like this Thórr god lady is comin'\nhere to put us through our paces and see\nif we all measure up.
I don't care if she IS a god—she has\nno right to judge any of us!
And I fail to understand why she would\ncarefully explain her scheme to you\nbefore undertaking it.
Unless she is attempting to lure you\ninto some manner of trap?

I don't think it's a trap—Thórr is just
obsessed with testing us mortals.
You'd be surprised how often this
kind of thing happens to us.

She's always saying things to us like,
＂I'm giving you this challenge, so show
me you have the strength to prevail!＂
...And so forth.
Well, that's all fine and dandy for a god,\nbut it sure does suck for the poor sap\nwhat's gettin' put through the wringer!
Yes, it does get very old.
She sounds like a difficult person.\nEr, or a difficult god, I guess?
Well, at least now we have some idea of\nwhat we're dealing with—as well as why\nyou think Alfonse has come here.
Indeed, Alfonse was the one who told\nme about all of you in the first place.
It's a lucky thing that I was able\nto find you on the first try!
Feels a little deus ex machina to me,\nbut what the hell do I know?
I wish we had something more to go on\nbesides vague hunches.
Well, I don't know if this will help,\nbut a bunch of our friends disappeared\nat the same time my brother was taken.
If that is all Thórr's doing, she may have\nbrought them to this world as well.
Do you think Thórr is using your friends\nas part of her plan to test us?

It's a possibility. Anyway, if there have
been any weird incidents around here
lately, it might be an indication that
my missing friends are close by.
And if we find them, they might be able\nto lead us to Thórr or Alfonse!
＂Weird incidents＂ is casting a\nfairly wide net, don't you think?
One of the villages nearby had some\ncarrots go bad in the field! Is that the\nkind of thing you're lookin' for?
Oh, and I heard about a town where\neverybody keeps oversleeping!

And my hair has been all split ends
lately—I hope that IS Thórr's doing
so it returns to normal after I kick
her butt all the way back to heaven!
No. I mean, yes, split ends have been\ndriving me crazy as well, and I'd be\nthrilled if I could blame Thórr for that...

But I mean the other one—the one about
folks oversleeping. Are they just missing
the first rooster crow, or are they so
deeply asleep you can't wake them up?
Uh, all I heard was that there are\nsome folks who just won't wake up...
We've had similar incidents on our world;\nit's possible one of our friends is involved!
Sounds like it's time to head over\nand take a look for ourselves.
